First time visit.  Great customer service and big portions, with good prices.  Ramen noodles was smooth and good flavor.  However, the soup was bland and the habanero dipping sauce wasn't even hot. Chili oil tasted stale.  The meat wasn't fresh.  It tasted like it was prepared several days earlier and then warmed up with the microwave.  BTW: I don't think this is a Japanese Ramen restaurant because the wait and cooking staff were Latinos and they were speaking Spanish.< /Text>

<userid>102918253898437847981<//userid>< review>
Zetton on it!  Zetton on it!

Ramen Zetton, the popular Costa Mesa ramen shop, has a new branch nearby me in Cypress.  For their soft opening, Ramen Zetton has priced their ramen bowls from $5 - $7.  Being a ramen lover & not one to pass up a discount, I hurried down to Ramen Zetton, eagerly awaiting slurping up some piping hot ramen.

The traditional ramen condiments are well represented - chili oil, white pepper grinder, vinegar, red chili pepper & house made spicy miso chili paste.

The house made spicy miso chili paste has a definite kick to it.  Not for spice weaklings.

I went for their signature Sesame Miso Tantan ramen ($7, reg. price $8.50)-

The tantan ramen broth is thick, almost curry-like.  Adding the entire jar of spicy miso chili paste, the broth became almost akin to marinara.  Plus, a splash of vinegar, some chili pepper, a drizzling of chili oil, freshly ground white pepper & a splash or 2 of vinegar. The vinegar is what really kicked the flavor profile up a notch.   Hearty & rich, the sesame miso tantan consisted of a special blend of sesame & miso, chicken broth, green onion, ground pork & vegetable puree.  The ramen had a good bite to it.  My preference would've enjoyed them more al dente, but I was not disappointed with the wonderfully thick broth & juicy chunks of ground pork.  At $7, a delicious bowl that's a must get!

Not feeling soup today?  Ramen Zetton's simplistic menu also has various rice dishes & gyoza for your consideration.

Service was good.  I arrived a few minutes before opening.  The father of the owner of Ramen Zetton was running the place.  The cook called in sick & one from the Costa Mesa location was brought in to save the day.  My water was refilled on a couple occasions & I was even given containers of the spicy miso chili paste to take home, w/o asking.  Not a place for large groups, seating is minimal with a few tables, booths & bar seating.

Parking is in private lot.  Hard to spot from the street, Ramen Zetton is located behind Oodles of Noodles Pho Restaurant & adjacent to Poki Roll.

Hurry & get down to Zetton!  Ramen Zetton serves up soothing bowls of ramen that are priced cheaper than their competitors.  The sesame miso tantan ramen was a winner & I'm eagerly anticipating trying their other ramen offerings.  I can't procrastinate, though, as I want to take advantage of Ramen Zetton's soft opening pricing.  Hungry for soup? Check out Ramen Zetton!

Highly recommend!
NOMNOMNOMNOMNOMNOMNOM<//review>

<user_id>112923256788955138104< /user_id>< user_name>
Pete Shieh< /user_name>
<date>1470258053632</date>< Rate>
3</Rate>
< text>
Former place for Cambinos and Teriyaki Monkey Wave rises Ramen Zetton. If you've been to this location, you would know how small this kitchen and seating is. I would say it seats about 24-30 people max.  Lots of parking in the lot, near by Icon (For you craft beer people)

As for the Ramen, prices are still discounted for Classic ($5), Old School ($5), Special Salt ($6), Special Soy ($6). Of course, we tried one of each.  The noodles for the $5 are thinner (Chuka-Soba), while the Ramen for the $6 are thicker. The broth for the Classic tasted packaged, the Old school Shoyu had a light soy (my favorite) and the Specials had this Vegetable broth which was a bit too much I thought.

Non of the broth tasted in depth, unlike those day long tonkotsu broths but for what you get, it's okay. The chicken that does come with the noodle tasted like shoyu braised with sugar and that was just okay too. Kitakata is nearby, personally I would go there instead.

Service here with one person is pretty awesome I have to say, even with a packed house.
Yep check in gets you free soda currently.  I will have to make another trip to try the other noodles.</text>

<Text>Just recently went to a wedding here and it was okay. The ceremony spot was small and cute. The layout of the venue is a bit odd and I didn't care for the uneven terrain every few steps. I saw a few people trip which didn't seem very safe. The reception area was very rustic and well themed but they only had port-a-potty's which was such a turn off for a wedding. So gross to use in our wedding attire. I wouldn't come here again or book them based on that alone. One of the staff members said this place has been here for several years so you would think they would make indoor bathrooms a priority but I guess not. Food was okay but no vegetarian entree option and nothing was super tasty. Near the end of the night, the bartender cut off my friend who was drinking and she was not even drunk. She was so embarrassed because of that and they went to so far to tell the Bride that she was cutoff. I would have been livid had I been the Bride. You don't interrupt my night to tattle on a friend. She hadn't been aggressive nor rude to anyone when they cut her off and yet they still seemed to make a scene about it. It really turned me off to this venue. I felt really bad for my friend since she had actually gone up a couple times for me and the Groom's mother for drinks as a good gesture. Overall, this venue left a sour taste in my mouth for recommending them to anyone.</Text><Pics>None< /Pics>< resp>

<rating>4</rating><review>My family loves it here! My parents, grandma, and I used to meet here for lunch at least two times a month, pre-COVID. It is a popular spot, and the food is phenomenal! I always get the Street Fair Noodle without bacon (allergy), and it is always delicious.

Honestly though, the biggest highlight here is the fact that my mom can order more than one dish, and it isn't a plain salad. She has some fairly severe food allergies, and this is one of a handful of restaurants in the entire county where she can eat. We are so excited and thankful that they are willing and able to make the modifications she needs, to be able to enjoy Thai food again!<//review><Pics>None</Pics><Response>None</Response>< Gmap_id>

< Review>
This is our favorite place for date night and to take family when they're in town. The food NEVER disappoints and the restaurant itself is stunning! They have a good variety of options, everything I've tried is delicious, and for the most part they're consistent when it comes to flavor and portions, although sometimes things are much spicier than a previous time having the same dish. Drinks and desert are great! However, we do have a big complaint when it comes to some of the service. The host has an attitude and gives us a hard time about seating. They always say we'll have to wait anywhere from 30 minutes to hours... really, HOURS?? The ridiculous part is that there are ALWAYS empty tables and we end up basically demanding to be seated in one of the several empty tables after being brushed off either to the bar or to the patio when it's freezing out. Mind you, we try making a reservation every time and the phone is either busy or they say they aren't taking any, yet there remain several empty tables each time they say this. The waiters and bartenders are usually pretty nice, so we tip a good amount. I was also disappointed that after our waiter (well, bartender since they never sat us at an empty table) offered to box up the half of my meal I hadn't eaten, and found later when I opened it that she did not put the tails from my prawns that I had set aside in the trash and instead MIXED THEM WITH MY FOOD. What?? It had to have been obvious to her and it was just plain rude or laziness. We are easy to please and courteous, so after having the same problems so many times after coming here and spending $100-200 each time, I'm pretty disappointed and ready to find a new spot.</Review>

One of the worst experiences I have ever had. We made a reservation but were still forced to wait for our table. Once at our table we were ignored by our waitress for 30 minutes. My friend and I happen to be the only minorities in a Thai restaurant that was otherwise completely white this evening. After 30 minutes our waitress finally comes to take our orders and apologies saying "it's my first day". But somehow she managed to check up on nearby tables around us multiple times while we waited the whole time. We voiced our displeasure and then were told "you guys are the ones being mean". At that point we were already in a bad mood and the food was nothing special. I left a 10% tip to reflect the service but was chastised by our waitress despite me explaining we had horrible service and my tip reflected it. The restaurant seemed very elitist and it's hard not to believe this wasn't a race issue based on the evidence. I would never recommend this place again, there are better hole in the wall Thai restaurants in Santa Rosa, ones that are able to serve you without the subtle racism.<//Text>

<Text>One of my favorite places to eat. Location is pretty good since Montgomery Village is rarely totally full on parking. Customer service is nice. Green curry is great, pad thai is great, lamb shanks are great (even though I was skeptical about the Sriracha choice at first). The salad was a bit salty. I love the firecracker shrimp as a starter. Tempura is good, fire chicken is good (maybe a little salty). Portions aren't huge, but with sharing an appetizer and eating a meal, I think it's enough. I see other people leaving with boxes regularly, so I assume I just really REALLY like the food.

Good desserts too (not sure if they still do desserts since last time I got one was a few years back).<//Text><pics>None</pics></record>

< name>
Li Li< /name>
< time>
1562355461338< /time>
<Resp>None<//Resp>< rate>
3</rate>
< Pics>
None< /Pics>
< user_id>
103349044967310521161<//user_id>
<text>Very nice ambience, different from many other Thai places whose ambition is to simply blend in and get by.
This was our first visit. We just dropped in for a quick lunch. The wait was reasonable. Staffs were pleasantly professional with none of that family run business vibe. This is a good sign and one that set apart Sea Thai from being one of the average Thai restaurants.
We ordered the northern style curry noodle, aka the famous "Kao Soi" we have heard so much from youtube peeps; ..and Spicy beef noodle soup.
For the spicy noodle-I call this the Thai Pho, it consisted of rice noodle, pieces of green, bean sprout, sliced jalapeno, and basil in clear broth. The broth (ahh )had that lovely depth of clean naturally obtained pork/chicken bones flavor. This was the best part and the most important element of this Pho. My eyes popped at first sip..Mmm..yum. the noodle was a tad overcooked but ok; the beef slices were plentiful but a bit too thick and therefore tough. This can be easily fixed by slice that beef thinly when it is half frozen, then place the beef slices on top of noodle and drench the hot beautiful broth from the top...voila! That's how I like it..I don't know about you. :)) (cost $16)
As for kao soi, there's much adjustments to be done. Let's start with the choice of egg noodle. It was too skinny! and, therefore, could not withstand the steamy curry. As the noodle continue to be cooked in that hot broth, by the time we could handle the noodle it was already overcooked. Also, all other components were lost in that thick stew like curry, so thick. The chicken slices and shrimp in it too were tough and chewy. (cost $20)
Between the two I might go with Pho again, perhaps asking for tofu or chicken instead, if allowed.
a Friendly FYI to staffs: when serving noodle dishes, please provide chopsticks as soon as you know there will be noodle, since it's the utensils appropriate for noodle consumption.
To be continued.</text>< gmapID>
0x80844876f85fd6ad:0x64110fd659a3245c<//gmapID>

<Resp>None< /Resp><UserId.>112011587338707480261< /UserId.><Pics>None< /Pics>< Review>
Oh yeah!
Frequent diner's card here would give us plenty of miles, but it doesn't exist. We love SEA Thai and it may be telling that they always recognize us.OK so it's only a few blocks from home - but that doesn't stop us from enjoying the fare and service here.
It really is SEA Thai Bistro as the SEA is an acronym for South East Asian...
They have an excellent menu and wine list as well as some tasty micro-brews.
It is not all Thai cuisine, but Asian-pacific fusion presented in artistic fashion.
The flavors are always extraordinarily pleasing. The specials are just that.
Do NOT tell all your friends about this local gem - it's very nice to get a seat easily and enjoy the personalized service. Just kidding really - take your friends thaty will thank you.</Review>

<GmapID>0x80844876f85fd6ad:0x64110fd659a3245c</GmapID><Pics>None< /Pics>< Rating>
5</Rating>
<Time>1397783628883< /Time><username>Elaine Lucia<//username>< review>
I was at Dale and Tony's restaurant, Thai Ginger Bistro when it opened in a tiny space in downtown Petaluma several years ago. A few years later they sold that  and opened SEA Thai.

I have eaten countless times at SEA, and I will really miss them when they leave Petaluma. But I will have no problem driving to any of their other locations (Santa Rosa, Marin), because it is so worth it.

Tony is a genius, it's that simple. The food is sublime - so fresh, so beautiful, so flavorful. And the service is genuinely warm, welcoming and friendly. They greet you with their lovely smiles, and really do everything they can to not only please you, but to surprise and delight.

I can't recommend SEA Thai Restaurant highly enough. They certainly deserve every accolade, and I look forward to their continued success.

This a MUST visit dining experience!</review>

< review>
I have been eating here for a few years now and I have noticed a serious decline in the Pad Thai noodles entree. The last time i had it the noodles were gummy and stuck together the sauce was a bit strong, and I had only 2 prawns in the whole dish! I don't personally like how the alfalfa sprouts or whatever they are, are not tossed in the entree. I wont be eating here anymore, it was good when it was good:(< /review>

< review>
Amazing food, especially the appetizers!!!! Doesn't look like much from the outside, but worth the trip in. Service was friendly and fast, great wine selection, but it's the food that really sets this place apart. For main dishes, we oredered the red pumpkin curry and the green curry. The pumpkin really stood out. If you like spicy food get this extra spicy. The appetizers that are to die for: panko-crusted tofu, mushroom potstickers, deep-fried mushrooms with peanut sauce, and spring rolls which you wrap in lettuce and pile up with topping and sauce. Super yum! We'll be back here every time we come to Santa Rosa.<//review>
< pictures>
None<//pictures>
< Resp>

<Gmap_id>0x80844876f85fd6ad:0x64110fd659a3245c</Gmap_id></record></dataset><record>
<pics>None< /pics><Resp>None<//Resp>< Text>
We were on vacation in Santa Rosa and looking for a new seafood place to eat. Sea Thai Bistro was perfect. The entire decor was right for the seafood place, flying fish and jellyfishes by the ceiling added very cool atmosphere to the restaurant. Bistro has a very cool patio, we had to wait for our table there but it was worth it.
Dinner: we had an Alaskan halibut with steamed veggies + green beans, they were super tasty and all dish was presented with the spicy green sauce.
The entire food was phenomenal, full of flavors and spices. We loved it. We also ordered a bottle of Sauvignon Blanc from Balverne winery at Russian River Valley- an excellent complement to our exotic sea dish.
Dessert: we had a panna cotta
presented in a very elegant way and it was delicious also.
Our weiter Tom did a great job, we had just one misunderstanding about bottled italian water but it was fixed right the way. The water was amazingly smooth and very good. Overall we had a very good experience and we will be back for sure.
Tony Ounpamornchai ,you and the entire team did very good job, thank you all.</Text>

< Rating>
5</Rating>
<Review>Valentino's Pizza location is one of my favorite pizza restaurants in Costa Mesa. It's conveniently in a shopping plaza on Fairview and Wilson, so you can't miss it. I have ordered from here many times both dining in and for delivery. The portions are generous and made with fresh ingredients. You can really taste the difference when compared to other pizza restaurants.

Some of my reasons on why I choose this location rather than others is because of the quick friendly service, generous portions, and price. If you decide to for carry out, it takes about 15 minutes. Other places I am waiting for 20 - 25 minutes, which is absolutely ridiculous. There are also no gimmicks at Valentino's Pizza, just friendly service and quality food.

My favorite pizza here is the BBQ Chicken. The pizza is packed with so much flavor and is just an amazing pizza. I also recommend the calzones. Go with the steak and you won't be disappointed. I heard good things about the desserts, but I'm generally stuffed because it's so much food.

I highly recommend Valentino's Pizza. The food is delicious and they provide quality service. Keep in mind they also offer pizza delivery because other locations do not. There's is no other pizza restaurant in Costa Mesa that compares!</Review>< Pics>

<name>Scot Parker</name>< time>
1483940438185</time>
<Rating>5< /Rating>< text>
My wife and I have been members here for a while, and I want to pay this business back in a small way, so here I am. We alternate between scheduling our massages 5-10 days in advance and booking the day before or the day of our appointment depending on what our work schedules are like and how much stress we are currently experiencing. In any case, the staff is helpful and accommodating. We of course can't count on booking with a specific therapist when we book with so little notice, but luckily every therapist we've met has done an admirable job, and we have never had a bad experience here. This tendency to occasionally book at the last minute has in fact been beneficial, as my wife and I have both met therapists that way that we probably would not have otherwise met, as we both met therapists fairly early on that we were quite happy to continue booking when they are available.

I'd like to specifically compliment three therapists - Scott, Briana, and Hernan. All three are friendly, really know what they are doing, and are responsible for the best massages I've received in my life. All three consistently work extremely hard during their massages, and strive to make sure that the customer's particular needs are met. Much of my work is physical (I do extensive field work as a scientist and work as a SCUBA instructor on the side) so I frequently come in with deep knots, extensive muscle soreness, and heavy tension. With all three of these therapists I've felt like my mind was being read, so intuitively were they able to isolate and dig in to each knot and tense muscle group. All three are also quite strong; I like heavy, hard pressure, particularly in my back and arms, and I have never been disappointed. Scott, Briana, and Hernan - if you see this review, you have a very satisfied customer, and I think you three are awesome!

The operation itself is well-organized and efficient. Booking can be conveniently done over the phone, online, or in person, and I've never failed to receive an emailed reminder before my appointment. The rooms and bedclothes are clean, the music is soft and pleasant, and the general ambiance is quite relaxing. The aromatherapy scents are pleasant without being overpowering, and the lotions used don't seem to leave an unpleasant scent or residue. The owner, Mitchell, also makes it a point to talk with the customers to ensure we are happy and to make us feel welcome and valued.

I look forward to being a patron here for a long time to come!< /text>

<Text>Best prices on gas in town. The 91 octane costs less per gallon then most places 87 octane.

Costco does not offer an 89 octane fuel.

I have fuelled a 2008 Chevrolet Impala and 1996 Ford Crown Victoria with Costco's 91 octane and have had no performance issues unlike at some cheap gas stations.

A Costco membership card is required to fuel any vehicle at Costco.< /Text>< pics>

<user>114233381502606719893< /user>< Review>
The staff are very nice and friendly. I have 2 reasons for giving a low rating. 1. The restroom which USED to be open to the public now has a restroom sign on the door, but is padlocked and not available for storage renter's use. So for the past month or so, whenever I go to my unit to go thru it I have to either leave what I've taken out outside of my storage or try to hurry to put it all back into my unit (which is a large unit FILLED) and drive to the Starbucks or Panda Express on the corner before I piss my pants. 2. The dumpsters are locked now. Have been for almost a week. I see no point in this. It's like the people running the facility want it looking trashy by making their customers put their garbage BY the dumpster. Just a FYI, that's how it looks. Trashy. These 2 problems are very rude inconveniences that make me want to take my business else where and not recommend this facility to anyone.</Review>

<Date>1386364683475<//Date><Rate>5< /Rate>< review>
My experience at Public Storage was one of relief. Kae and Michelle made it easy to work with them and not being pressured when what I consider valuables are in their storage facility. Bad experiences in the past led to unjustly relinquishing me of my storage when all I wanted was my personal pictures and paperwork. When the storage (not Public Storage) is going to auction my things anyway, why not take at least half of the storage cost to get my baby pictures and classwork, sport medals, etc., priceless memories. To think that all the person who buys the storage is going to do is throw those things in the dumpster was disheartening. I am ranting because you can guess that it has had an impact on me. But Public Storage made it easy for me to downsize if needed be and made it a simple process to move out. Thank you very much.<//review>

It could be this, this or this.  Which leads me to question, do service tech earn commission on repairs? In other words, the more parts and labor they sell, the bigger their paycheck?

Is this ethical?  Sadly, I ran into this same issue about a year or two ago with Anderson and my AC condenser. The repair estimate was $6K.  I ended up fixing it myself for $200 and it's worked perfectly ever since.

Today‚Äôs repair estimate  $1,788 + $68 for the service call. The parts, which I found online, are less than $285, and I question if they are both necessary. Labor time to replace these two suggested parts, or three suggested parts is 45 minutes for an experienced tech,  double for a novice.

I proceeded to show her the issue and she removed the drawers from my bathroom sink in order to look at the plumbing.

After looking at the plumbing she indicated that she could clear the clog but it would happen again due to the drain. I explained that the purpose of the service call was to evaluate and take the steps needed to permanently resolve the issue and I was happy to replace all plumbing if needed to resolve this issue.

<Time>1613984028526< /Time>< Rate>

<Review>Update:
Erin, Anderson's Client Relations Manager reached out via email and explained their policy of flat rate per type of the job.  She offered 15% off on the water pressure regulator job and removed the charge for accessing the valve. While I recognize the effort to provide good customer care (along with multiple text, email and phone call asking for feedback)  I cannot say I'm remotely happy about this flat rate charge that's 3-4 time higher than being reasonable.

===========================================================
Anderson Plumbing's charge is absurdly high! I had a technician come to fix a leaky waterline going into the fridge. while doing that he also found the water pressure was high and I agreed to have the water pressure regulator replaced.

He had to cut a small hole on the drywall to access the pipe, which took him 30 seconds, and the charge is $323. Note this is only for cutting the hole, not including any repair work, and they will not fix the drywall afterwards. The actual repair work of replacing the water supply line's connection valve is another $323, which I'm ok with, since at least the technician spent 30 minutes on it.

The most ridiculous one is the $1,485 charge for replacing the water pressure regulator. The part is $180 according to the technician, and it's a quick job taking him literally less than 10 minutes using only a plumbers plier. I found out afterwards a reasonable cost for this should be in the $300 range including the part, and feel quite bad not doing enough research and being an informed customer beforehand. I wish everyone else considering calling them have the chance to read the reviews beforehand and be aware of their practice of overcharging to an outrageous extent.

I do agree that it was easy for me to make the appointment, and the technician came on time and finished the job quickly in a professional manner. But I'd not be able to recommend their services to anyone due to the extremely unreasonably high cost.< /Review>< pics>
None<//pics>

Anderson came in at a reasonable price but the technician, Drew (Andrew), included additional incentives that persuaded us to go with them. < Text>
James B from Anderson is a fantastic plumber. I thought the drain from the toilet to the main line was blocked but he ran a few tests and determined the blockage was actually in the low-flow toilet itself. The problem was that the flush handle was not being held down long enough with the result that  the bowl was getting insufficient water so  toilet paper was not being pushed through the trap (located in the toilet) to the sewer pipe. On these low flow toilets you can't just press and release the handle- if you do the flapper valve will close prematurely. You must press and hold the handle down to keep the flapper valve open until all the water in the tank has entered the bowel.</Text>

<rate>1<//rate>< text>
When I first called Anderson Plumbing it was to fix the thermostat on my air conditioner. They told me that the unit was old (7 years old) and could not be replaced. That I would need to put in a new unit with new air conditioners. Having spent thousands of dollars with this company I figured that I had enough experience with them so that I could call them to fix a simple problem with the hot water in my shower. When they came I was told that I needed a new water softener unit for another few thousand dollars but my shower was fixed for the time being.
A couple of days later,when I had the same problem with the hot water in my shower, I made another appointment. At this appointment ,with another technician, I was told that I needed a different unit ,for another few thousand dollars, and the unit the first technician told me I needed wouldn't work. At this point I decided that I needed a second opinion from another company. In the meantime I found that the last guy they sent out had broken the hot cold water mixer on my shower. They escalated the problem to a repair supervisor who came out that week. He told me that they would have to replace the mixer on my shower, at no cost to me, and would call me in 2 days with an update as well as the exact cost of the new water softener unit he said I needed.
Two weeks later I still hadn't heard back from him. On the third week I received a message on my machine stating that the mixer had to be ordered from the manufacturer  and he would call me back the next day to discuss it. He had already tols me that it had to be replaced and I had foolishly assumed that he would do that first thing not three weeks later.
Three months later I still hadn't heard back from Anderson when I received an email message telling me it was time to make a service appointment on my air conditioners. I wrote back that I wouldn't be making any appointments with Anderson and to please remove me from their mailing list. That day I got a phone call from a very nice understanding lady who stated she was new to the job but that she was trying to straighten out problems that customer had had. She told me she would call Jose,the supervising technician who had come out the last time, and get back to me. True to her word she called me back the next day and informed me that she had ordered the part. She offered to call me every week to keep me updated which I declined.
Finally,after months, I got a call from her that the new part had come in and we made an appointment to install it.
The next time I tried to use my shower I found that only scalding hot water was coming out. No cold water to mix the hot water with. I called them to tell them what the situation was and she offered to send Jose back out to check on the problem. She informed me that since I had a tankless hot water system sometimes it took some time for the new unit to adjust. Now this explanation made no sense to me and if it makes sense to you then I'd suggest Anderson for your plumbing needs. It seems that in fixing one problem they always create a new one. To have them come out to try to fix it would be free but even at free it's far to expensive for me.
I wouldn't recommend Anderson to anyone  They're always   trying to sell you something new and can't seem to be able to do what they are hired to do correctly.
Stay far far away from this company.

Mark Schwartz<//text>

<rating>5</rating><text>Smelled gas coming from beneath our stove, which is very alarming. Shut off the valve underneath, aired out the kitchen, but hours later still smelled a bit of gas. Called something like 5 different plumbers asking for help as I have three young kids in the house and a wife who is due to have our fourth ANY MINUTE! Very much a serious situation. Despite this, every plumber I called either didn't respond or they were too busy to help. Then, I realized a family member recently used Anderson and she gave me the name and number of the actual technician that helped her out so I gave them a call and asked for James by name.  They appreciated how urgent this situation was, and James came out right away. He and his teammate arrived and were pleasant to work with from the start. They were always professional, and obviously experts at what they do. Throughout the entire process they communicated with us frequently so we always knew what was going on, what progress they've made, what their recommendations are, and what options we had. They were also very clear and direct with the costs associated with each option, and we never felt pressured into paying some exorbitant amount for optional services. They worked hard the entire time, being very sensitive to my family's particular situation. After the gas leak was fixed, James came back a few more times in the following days to do further tests to make absolutely certain things were done right and that everything was still holding up after they made the repairs. He even came out personally to meet with underground leak detection services (a third party), spoke to city gas company on our behalf to get our gas turned back on, and worked directly with the city inspectors office to get all the appropriate inspections and paperwork in order. Now, my family has gas service again! More importantly, this means we have a working clothes dryer, furnace, and HOT WATER. I could not have asked for a better experience in an otherwise really difficult situation.< /text><pictures>None< /pictures><Resp>None</Resp>< gmap_id>

The technician installed the blower motor and it worked for less than 24 hours.  Anderson came back and this time brought back a salesman who tried to pressure me into spending 9-10 THOUSAND dollars on a completely new system.  I felt very uncomfortable about the sales tactics and I could tell that my technician was also uncomfortable.  Eventually the salesperson left and the technician agreed to try a simple remedy, adding refrigerant to the system.  They were originally going to try to charge me $200 for this, but decided to spare me the expense.  The system worked for only a few hours.  I eventually changed the outlet and that got the system working for a couple of weeks.

It broke again, and after talking to other professionals in the area and my family friend back at home about it, they explained that I was completely ripped off and completely overcharged for something that failed to work.  They also explained that the prices that they were quoting me for a new system were completely absurd.  I feel completely taken advantage of; the company realized that my spouse and I were not savvy in the HVAC realm and they pounced on the opportunity to make as much money from us as possible.

I ultimately hired a new professional to fix my broken system and they explained that the motor that was installed by Anderson had already broke and also that there were other fixes to try prior to replacing the blower motor originally. I explained that I know that they took advantage of me and that I was uncomfortable with their sales tactics and they just choose to slander the professional that I used to fix the problem and try to affix the blame on me in any way possible.

< Review>
Larry was very courteous, answered my questions and tried to trouble shoot the problem.    He was on time, respected my property.  What he did not do was remove the trap.  I did not ask him to but when he ran water and could not reproduce the back up of water in the sink, he might have thought of that.  I thought of it later the night and asked the next person who looked at the sink when it backed up again to do that.  We found a child's toothbrush which had obviously been in there for some time.  I am not faulting him but the next time I would definitely make sure the trap be removed from a sink that is backing up.

I also had Zak B. out for the same problem.  Again he ran water, tried to reproduce the blockage.  We went over everything that had been done the day before, we checked the clean out on the side of the building and then I asked him to remove the trap on the sink.  He did and we found a child's toothbrush in the trap.  Again if I had not asked to have it removed the problem would have recurred.  I am happy I asked but I think the technician should know to remove a trap if they can't reproduce the blockage with running water.  Something has to be causing the sink to backup several times.< /Review>

< Text>
I called Anderson to have a broken disposer replaced. Calling the job in already a great experience - ''How can I make you smile today?'' just works! Scheduling was without problems and I got called 30 minutes before the technician arrived. Justin M. impressed me right away, because he listened to my problem description, then assessed the work involved, presented me with the options available. I chose, he did the rest - a sizable job as it turned out. In-between and after having finished, he warned me that, perhaps, another unrelated problem might arise in the near future. He counseled me on the work to be done, if that were the case. Justin explained everything very well. He also asked me if there were other problems and, on me mentioning one, he took care of it. The parts that he needed were on the Anderson truck - they are fully stocked as the advertisement says. Justin left the job site clean and tidy. The part that he had mentioned might be on the brink of failure actually did fail a few hours later. I called it in, the time was set and Justin took care of the rusted out part the next day, same time. No fuzz, no huff and puff, Anderson and Justin just did it. I had used this company before, and was happy, but it has gotten even better!</Text>

<time>1501022984115< /time>< Text>
Tried Anderson Plumbing, Heating, and Air for the first time. Having only one full bath, it was a bit of an emergency when the shower wouldn't drain, and dripping faucets were rapidly filling the shower stall. Technician James, attempted to clear the blockage, but only got 2 feet into the drain. After informing him of old cast iron pipes in the crawl space beneath our house, he called a camera specialist, Ricardo, to determine the problem. We needed a new trap and 10 foot length of modern-day "code" pipe. James was able to temporarily stop the dripping faucets. Unfortunately, we weren't able to schedule the fix-up for a week later.

One week later: Larry, a very knowledgeable man with plenty of on-the-job experience, and a supervisor as well, arrived about 8:30 AM (on time), fully explained all of the work that was to be done, and answered all of our questions. Then he went right to work. The beneath the house work was accomplished pretty quickly, but the new, Moen, single handle faucet kit was a bit of a challenge. Larry had to remove an area of tile, and saw through 2-inch concrete and lathe in our "vintage" shower stall. When the job was completed (by mid-afternoon), the shower drained well (with its modern, 4 inch pipe), and we had a shiny Moen faucet/plate and shower head. They were so well-installed that one couldn't tell that they were replacements. No damage to the existing tile and well-sealed.

On the same-day that James and Ricardo came out, (at different times), I was only charged $42. Ricardo prepared the cost, with options. In my opinion, the fee for the option that I chose, was fair, considering the time, labor, and parts involved. On repair day, no attempt to oversell, no surprises. My white tiled bathroom was left clean, and undamaged. Larry even wore shoe covers to protect my dark hardwood floors and oriental rugs where he had to pass through the house.

I definitely will call Anderson again for its caring, knowledgeable, experienced, professional service for plumbing repairs on my OLD house. Thank you, James, Ricardo, and Larry.< /Text>

Our normal camera charge is $250.00, and an additional fee to place findings on a flash drive for your records. However, when a client needs a "Plumbers Report" there is more to just the camera-ing of the line. Because the city will not take the report from a homeowner, only a licensed plumber- our technicians have to camera the line, place the findings on a disc, write up an official findings report, take these to the city and file the report along with their form- this is why the price increased. I was also informed that the city will not do anything regarding roots in the line, corrosion or build up. There has to actually be a break, or collapse in the line for them to come out and repair/replace. If the line is able to be hydro-jetted to clear out roots or buildup- they will expect the homeowner to take care of this at their expense. I hope this gives a little more insight to your concern. Areas that could be improved:

1.  Electronic contract administration.  i.e. could not open email to print/save contract which we changed a few times and called twice for a final copy which I still haven't received.

3.  Patchwork to drywall.  i.e. we relocated the thermostat and the hole from existing location was poorly done.

These are easy things for the company to fine tune in their administration/installation process.< /text>

< Text>
I did not have a good experience with this company. I had them out to move a gas line and repair a leak coming from one of the fixtures in the upstairs bathtub. I usually try and stay home when people are working on the house for supervision and to answer questions, but this time I couldn't. Upon arriving home after work I found a 1 ft by 2 ft hole in the bathroom ceiling that was in the room adjacent to where the gas line was being moved and I received a message saying that I could not use my bathroom shower as the pipe below had been cracked. I do realize things happen on a jobsite, but this was a bit ridiculous. And to top it off, when I reached out to the plumber for clarification, he stated it was my fault and that I would have to pay to get everything fixed. He said he would "work with me" on the price but that he is "covered and took pictures." Being in the medical field, I liken this to a surgeon repairing a ACL, but in the meantime cutting the MCL. Apparently the gas line had fallen when he cut it which caused the hole in the spare bathroom ceiling and when he was unscrewing the drain plug, he broke the pipe below. After much argument, the plumber did agree to fix the pipe that was broke but I had to supply all of the parts and the hole in the ceiling I would have to fix. Overall, if you want your house to be in worse shape after you pay $1500, call this company.

After my review for this company I noticed that they had responded with a "we do not have you in our records, please call this number." I proceeded to call this number and express my concerns with their work. After leaving a message and waiting 2 weeks, I have now determined this must be an automated message by the company and this "we do not have your records on file" is a way to make them look like they care. Bad all around!!!<//Text>

<Rating>5< /Rating>< text>
This was my second experience with Anderson Plumbing, Heating and Air.  I was having issues with my upstairs bathroom sinks not draining.  I tried to fix it myself, but to no avail.  I decided to call Anderson Plumbing, Heating and Air because my previous experience with them was an excellent one.  I called a little later in the evening and was pleasantly surprised  that someone was there to take my call.  I was greeted with a warm, "Thank you for calling Anderson Plumbing, Heating and Air, how can I make you smile today?!"  What a nice way to greet your customers!  Right away, you know that you are going to be taken care of.  I was easily able to schedule an appointment.  The first appointment offered was on a Sunday.  That is so great that they could send someone over the weekend.  I knew I wasn't going to be home on Sunday so I made the appointment for the early 8-12pm window on Monday.  Usually when a company gives you a window of time, you can usually count on them coming at the end of the time, if not much later.  This is really inconvenient when you have to take half a day off of work just to wait for a technician.  Not the case with Anderson.  I got a call at 8am saying that the tech would arrive by 9am.  And he arrived by 9am!  Larry introduced himself, shook my hand, and asked for permission to enter my house.  Before he entered, he put on his booties without being asked.  After I explained my plumbing issue to him, he clearly explained what actions he needed to do and explained in detail what the cost was going to be.  I asked Larry if he would mind if I watched so I can learn how to fix a clog in the future.  He said, "Sure" and proceeded to educate me and explain step by step what he was doing and why and how the plumbing worked.  He was happy to do it and appeared genuinely proud of the work he was doing.  Many techs want to be left alone and don't want to be bothered.  Turned out that my drain issue was a bit complex.  Larry used his industrial auger, which put my 20 ft hand auger to shame.  When that did not work, be broke out the beast auger and that fixed the issue.  Despite having to go back and forth to the van to get supplies, despite having to go up and down and stairs, inside and outside the house, Larry stayed calm and collected, didn't mind removing and putting back on his booties.  When he finished his work upstairs, he cleaned up the entirety of his work area and then some.  He sprayed down the counters and glass with cleaner and he made sure he left the bathroom area nicer than when he arrived.  He even thanked me for my help, even though I was there observing to learn from him.  Larry recapped everything that he did, explained the warranty of his work, and made some recommendations without being one bit pushy or salesy.  I was so impressed by Larry's work ethic, professionalism, integrity, and passion for his craft.  Coincidentally, that day was "National Hug a Plumber Day".  To show my appreciation, I offered Larry a tip so that he can buy lunch or whatever.  He graciously said, "No thank you, it was my pleasure to serve you, use that to take your kids out to lunch."  What a great guy!

The next day, based on Larry's recommendation, William came over with his nifty video device.  In order to make sure that there were no other issues with my pipes, William fished his video camera down into my pipes.  We were able to clearly see inside the pipes, maybe 20 feet or so.  This was displayed on the video monitor.  When he was done, William said everything looked good, there was no additional blockage.  He recommended hydrojetting (washing) of the pipes, but at this point it was not an emergency, but should be done at some point in order to avoid future clogs.  I appreciated his honesty when he could have easily tried to upsell me.

This is a testament to what a great company Anderson is.  Built upon family values, they really take the time and effort to show that they care and appreciate their customers.  If you have any plumbing, heating or air issues, I recommend Anderson without reservation!</text>

< Review>
I needed some minor plumbing/fixture work done on my home to get it ready for a home inspection.  My typical plumber did not have availability within the time frame.  I remembered the AWSOME trucks I had seen around, and being a professional female myself, I thought I'd give them a try. Calling and scheduling the appointment was great--super professional without a long wait for service. The service charge was extremely reasonable as well. The guy arrived on time and was really nice.
Before entering the house, I showed him a water spicket that had a stripped handle on it. He said he would look at it before he left but it would be expensive (odd  I thought). One of the jobs was to have a "sticky" diverter (from bath to shower) loosened because it was gritty and difficult to manipulate.   No parts, not major work.  Problem:  the quote to have that done was $550!  Really.  $550.    I declined and showed him another bath tub  where the water stopper was not attached to the Kohler lever so the water would not drain.  He did not know how to fix the Kohler but suggested a toe tap drain.   This, I had to do because I needed it for an inspection. The charge: $330.  Really.  It took him 5 minutes.
He overheard me on the phone telling my real estate agent that the charge was too expensive and he apologized  stating that he didn't set the prices, he only enforced them.

After he left, I got a squirt bottle with vinegar and soaked and manipulated the gritty diverter.  Works just fine.  Really, Really disappointed.<//Review>

< Text>
Russel and John got tasked to correct a difficult Return Air ducting issue with a new install of a Lennox 4 ton HVAC unit in an older existing structure. The original Return ducting consisted of a single 12" round duct. The unit needed at least 1500 cfm, when it only had 600 cfm. I thought we could get another through the lower story into the mechanical room, but only a 6" was able to be installed due to framing and other mechanical systems interference. The solution,  since I did not want the exterior of the structure opened up, was to have the service tech, Russel, crawl up through a small opening in the ceiling of the outside mechanical room; upwards through a 2 story chase, in order to remove the existing 12" and cut in another 12' round to double that capacity. Both Russel and John never hesitated when evaluating the job. They jumped right in, finished in a remarkably short time, made the connections in extremely tight areas, worked cleanly and neatly. The A/C unit now produces the full 4 ton capacity with no problem. Kudos to these guys for their work and extremely positive attitudes, and know how; to be able to get a difficult remodel situation solved.
Thanks Guys.</Text>

<review>I contacted SDG& E about a gas smell in my foyer.  They came out and found no gas readings in the home yet checked out the system and found it was changing pressure enough to warrant a complete gas turnoff and lock.  That was on June 2nd.  That same evening I contacted Anderson Plumbing on the web and was contacted that same evening to schedule a technician to come out.

Chris B was very professional.  He and his associate went through the system thoroughly and methodically assessing the situation.  Unfortunately, with this older structure finding the problem was difficult.  But through a process of elimination, Chris was able to narrow it down to an single location and had a theory on the possible issue.  He then proceeded to let me know of the delay in completion do to the fact that he wanted to be sure and not demo my home any more by using a helium test to pinpoint the problem.

The next day the problem area was found and the repairs were down quickly.  Unable to get the County to move faster they were not able to come out on Friday to sign off on this.  The whole weekend was a "no Hot Water"  weekend.

On Monday we got the County Inspector(if you can call him that.)  He immediately treated you staff as if they we amature Craigslist Handymen.  Telling them they did the repair all wrong and used the wrong hardware and proceeded in accusing Chris of not being "qualified"  to do the work because he didn't have a certification card.  He even said this work wasn't finished,  made them change a flex line in the furnace to a hard line( not why he was here by the way) and walked out as Chris tried to explain to him where was mistaken and that he is a professional at his work.  Chris was then, after at least 15 minutes convinced the inspector that he was right.  The inspector basic conditionally approved the turn-on.  And wanted Chris to return to shut off everything later this week so he can come back out and inspect the fixes himself and the pressure reading as well.  Preposterous Crap!

Well Chris got the job done and he and his associate(sorry I for got his name) was supurb, and after six days my wife can now washer her hair.  That's all that matters.

Thanks Chris
Thanks Anderson.
